## 4. Application Load Balancer

```bash
# Find the LB
aws elbv2 describe-load-balancers \
  --query 'LoadBalancers[*].{Name:LoadBalancerName,ARN:LoadBalancerArn,DNS:DNSName,State:State.Code,Scheme:Scheme}'

# Target health — the single most important ALB check
aws elbv2 describe-target-groups --load-balancer-arn <lb-arn> \
  --query 'TargetGroups[*].{Name:TargetGroupName,ARN:TargetGroupArn,Port:Port,HealthPath:HealthCheckPath}'
aws elbv2 describe-target-health --target-group-arn <tg-arn> \
  --query 'TargetHealthDescriptions[*].{Target:Target.Id,Port:Target.Port,State:TargetHealth.State,Reason:TargetHealth.Reason}'

# Listeners & TLS
aws elbv2 describe-listeners --load-balancer-arn <lb-arn> \
  --query 'Listeners[*].{Port:Port,Protocol:Protocol,Cert:Certificates[0].CertificateArn}'
aws elbv2 describe-rules --listener-arn <listener-arn>

# Idle timeout — matters for SSE / Stream API
aws elbv2 describe-load-balancer-attributes --load-balancer-arn <lb-arn> \
  --query "Attributes[?Key=='idle_timeout.timeout_seconds' || Key=='access_logs.s3.enabled' || Key=='deletion_protection.enabled']"
```

**Look for:** all targets `healthy`; an HTTPS (443) listener with a valid ACM cert; HTTP→HTTPS redirect; **idle timeout long enough** for long-lived SSE connections (or your SSE pattern accounts for it); access logs enabled; deletion protection on; listener rules routing to the correct target groups (main API / stream / OAuth / legacy).

