## 5. CloudFront

```bash
aws cloudfront list-distributions \
  --query 'DistributionList.Items[*].{Id:Id,Domain:DomainName,Status:Status,Enabled:Enabled,\
Aliases:Aliases.Items,Origins:Origins.Items[*].DomainName}'

# Full config: behaviors, TTLs, origins, cert, protocol policy
aws cloudfront get-distribution-config --id <dist-id>
```

**Look for:** `Deployed` + `Enabled`; correct alternate domain names (CNAMEs) with an ACM cert **in us-east-1**; viewer protocol policy = redirect-to-HTTPS; origins correct (S3 for static assets, ALB for APIs); cache behaviors that **do not cache authenticated API or SSE responses** (forward auth headers, disable caching on those paths); Origin Access Control (OAC) for the S3 origin so the bucket isn't public; a response-headers policy (security headers) and WAF association if expected.

---

## 6. S3 (static assets)

```bash
aws s3 ls

# Public access block — critical
aws s3api get-public-access-block --bucket <bucket>

# Policy & ACL — confirm not world-readable
aws s3api get-bucket-policy --bucket <bucket> --query 'Policy' --output text 2>/dev/null | jq .
aws s3api get-bucket-acl --bucket <bucket>

# Encryption & versioning
aws s3api get-bucket-encryption --bucket <bucket>
aws s3api get-bucket-versioning --bucket <bucket>
```

**Look for:** all four public-access-block flags `true` (with CloudFront serving via OAC); default encryption enabled; versioning enabled (lets you roll back a bad asset deploy); bucket policy grants read **only** to the CloudFront OAC principal — no `"Principal":"*"` public reads.

---

## 7. ACM certificates

```bash
aws acm list-certificates --query 'CertificateSummaryList[*].{Domain:DomainName,ARN:CertificateArn}'
aws acm describe-certificate --certificate-arn <arn> \
  --query 'Certificate.{Status:Status,NotAfter:NotAfter,Renewal:RenewalEligibility,InUse:InUseBy}'
```

**Look for:** `ISSUED`; `NotAfter` comfortably in the future; auto-renewal eligible; each cert actually `InUseBy` the expected ALB/CloudFront. Remember CloudFront certs must live in **us-east-1**; ALB certs in the ALB's region.

---

## 8. WAF (if in use)

```bash
aws wafv2 list-web-acls --scope CLOUDFRONT --region us-east-1     # for CloudFront
aws wafv2 list-web-acls --scope REGIONAL --region <region>        # for the ALB
aws wafv2 get-web-acl --scope <scope> --region <region> --name <name> --id <id> \
  --query 'WebACL.Rules[*].{Name:Name,Action:Action,Priority:Priority}'
```

**Look for:** a Web ACL actually associated with the CloudFront distribution and/or ALB; managed rule groups enabled; rate-based rules present given this app controls physical devices.

---

## 9. Networking — security groups & VPC (least privilege)

```bash
# Inbound rules for the data-store SGs
aws ec2 describe-security-groups --group-ids <rds-sg> <redis-sg> <msk-sg> \
  --query 'SecurityGroups[*].{Name:GroupName,Id:GroupId,Ingress:IpPermissions}'

# VPC endpoints (private access to AWS services)
aws ec2 describe-vpc-endpoints \
  --query 'VpcEndpoints[*].{Service:ServiceName,State:State,Type:VpcEndpointType}'
```

**Look for:** RDS reachable only from the app SG on 3306, Redis only on 6379, MSK only on its broker ports — **no `0.0.0.0/0`** on any data store. Data stores in private subnets. VPC endpoints for S3/ECR/etc. if you're keeping traffic off the public internet.

---

## 10. IAM / IRSA (pod permissions)

```bash
aws iam get-role --role-name <irsa-role> \
  --query 'Role.{Name:RoleName,Trust:AssumeRolePolicyDocument}'
aws iam list-attached-role-policies --role-name <irsa-role>
aws iam list-role-policies --role-name <irsa-role>
```

**Look for:** the trust policy scoped to the cluster's OIDC provider **and** a specific namespace/service account (not a wildcard); attached policies scoped to only the resources that service needs (specific S3 bucket, specific secrets) rather than `*`.

---

## 11. Secrets & parameters

```bash
aws secretsmanager list-secrets \
  --query 'SecretList[*].{Name:Name,Rotation:RotationEnabled,LastChanged:LastChangedDate}'
aws ssm describe-parameters \
  --query 'Parameters[*].{Name:Name,Type:Type,LastModified:LastModifiedDate}'
```

**Look for:** DB/Redis/OAuth credentials stored here (not in manifests or images); rotation enabled where feasible; `SecureString` for SSM params. **Do not print secret values** into shared logs.

---

## 12. Observability & alarms

```bash
# Alarm inventory and current state
aws cloudwatch describe-alarms \
  --query 'MetricAlarms[*].{Name:AlarmName,State:StateValue,Metric:MetricName,Namespace:Namespace}' --output table

# Blind spots: alarms with no data
aws cloudwatch describe-alarms --state-value INSUFFICIENT_DATA \
  --query 'MetricAlarms[*].AlarmName'

# Currently firing
aws cloudwatch describe-alarms --state-value ALARM \
  --query 'MetricAlarms[*].AlarmName'

# Log groups exist and retain sensibly
aws logs describe-log-groups \
  --query 'logGroups[*].{Name:logGroupName,Retention:retentionInDays,Stored:storedBytes}' --output table
```

**Look for:** alarms covering RDS (CPU/connections/storage), Redis (memory/evictions), MSK (consumer lag/under-replicated partitions), ALB (5xx/target health/latency), CloudFront (5xx error rate); **no critical alarms stuck in `INSUFFICIENT_DATA`** (that's a monitoring blind spot); alarm actions wired to a real SNS topic; log groups with a defined retention (not "never expire" by accident, not too short).

---

## 13. DNS (Route 53)

```bash
aws route53 list-hosted-zones --query 'HostedZones[*].{Name:Name,Id:Id}'
aws route53 list-resource-record-sets --hosted-zone-id <zone-id> \
  --query 'ResourceRecordSets[?Type==`A` || Type==`CNAME`].{Name:Name,Type:Type,Target:AliasTarget.DNSName}'
```

**Look for:** the portal's records resolve to the correct CloudFront distribution / ALB; alias records rather than hardcoded IPs; health checks attached if you use DNS failover.

