# Portal UI Verification — Checklist

Manual walkthrough of the portal in the browser. Record **pass / fail + evidence** (screenshot, DevTools capture, correlation ID) for each item.

> ⚠️ **The control path actuates real appliances.** Do every control/diagnostic test against a **designated TEST device only** — never a live customer appliance. Confirm which environment and which device you're pointed at before you click anything that sends a command.

Tools you'll use throughout: browser **DevTools** → Network, Console, Application (cookies/storage) tabs. A couple of quick shell checks are included where faster.

---

## 1. Load & delivery

- Portal loads at the correct **prod URL** over **HTTPS** (valid cert, no browser warning).
- No **mixed-content** warnings; no errors in the **Console** tab on load.
- Static assets (JS/CSS/images) load from CloudFront/S3, not a dev origin — check the **Network** tab domains.
- Correct **build/version** is live (check a version string, `/version` endpoint, or build hash in asset filenames) — confirm it matches the intended release.
- Page title, favicon, and branding are the production ones (not staging).

```bash
# Security & cache headers in one shot
curl -sI https://<portal-url> | grep -iE \
 'strict-transport-security|content-security-policy|x-frame-options|x-content-type-options|referrer-policy|cache-control|server'
```

---

## 2. Authentication (OAuth)

- Hitting the portal while logged out **redirects to the OAuth login**.
- Valid credentials log in and land on the expected home/dashboard.
- **Refreshing the page keeps you logged in** (session persists).
- **Token refresh** works — stay past the access-token lifetime and confirm the session continues without a hard re-login (watch the Network tab for a refresh call).
- **Expired/invalid token** is handled gracefully (clean redirect to login, not a white screen or a raw error).
- **Logout** clears the session; hitting a back button or deep link afterward doesn't restore access.
- **Deep-link protection:** pasting an authenticated URL while logged out redirects to login rather than exposing the page.
- **Authorization / RBAC:** an agent sees and can act on **only the devices/actions their role permits**. Try (in a test account) to reach a device outside scope and confirm it's blocked — this is the most security-critical UI check for a device-control portal.

---

## 3. Navigation & core pages

- All primary nav links resolve — no dead ends or 404s.
- **Device list** loads; search, filter, sort, and pagination behave on a realistic data volume.
- **Device detail** page opens and shows current state.
- Deep-linking to a specific device by URL works and respects auth/RBAC.
- Browser **back/forward** behaves; refreshing a deep page doesn't break routing (SPA route handling).

---

## 4. Real-time updates (Stream API / SSE)

- On a device detail page, **state updates appear live** without a manual refresh.
- **Latency** between an actual state change (on a test device) and the UI reflecting it is acceptable.
- The stream **survives an idle period** — leave the page open several minutes and confirm updates still arrive (this catches ALB/CloudFront idle-timeout and edge-buffering issues that only appear in prod).
- **Reconnection:** toggle your network off/on (DevTools → Network → Offline) and confirm the stream reconnects and resumes without a full reload.
- Open the device in **two tabs** and confirm both receive updates consistently.
- Check the **Network** tab: the SSE/EventStream connection is open and receiving events (not repeatedly failing and retrying).

---

## 5. Diagnostics

- Run a diagnostic against a **test device**; results render correctly.
- **Loading state** shows while it runs; **error state** shows cleanly if it fails or times out.
- Results reflect real device data (cross-check against a known value).

---

## 6. Control path — highest caution ⚠️

Use a **designated test appliance**. Never issue control commands to a real customer device during verification.

- A control command from the UI **reaches the test device** and the device responds.
- The resulting **state change flows back** and the UI updates (ties into §4).
- **Confirmation UX:** destructive/impactful actions require a confirm step; there's clear feedback on success/failure.
- **Offline device:** controls are disabled or clearly error when the device is offline, rather than silently appearing to succeed.
- **Partial/failed delivery:** simulate a command that doesn't complete and confirm the UI communicates the true state (no false "success").
- **Guardrails:** rate limiting / bulk-action confirmation exist so an accidental click can't actuate many devices at once.
- **Permission enforcement:** an agent cannot send a control command to a device outside their authorized scope.
- **Audit trail:** every control action is recorded with **who** (agent identity), **what** (command), **when** (timestamp), and **which device** — verify the entry actually appears after your test action.

---

## 7. Legacy frontend

- The legacy UI **loads and functions** against the legacy API.
- **Auth** works for legacy (either its own login or SSO bridged from the new OAuth) — no separate broken login.
- Whatever functionality legacy still owns has **parity / correctness** for those flows.
- Navigation **between new and legacy** (if linked) works with no broken hand-offs or auth loss.

---

## 8. Error handling & resilience (user-facing)

- Simulate an **API failure** (e.g. block the API host in DevTools) and confirm the UI shows a graceful error, not a blank screen.
- **401 / 403 / 404 / 500** conditions each produce a sensible page or message.
- **Form validation:** invalid input is caught client-side with clear messages; server-side validation errors surface readably.
- **Timeouts** are handled (spinner doesn't hang forever; a retry or error appears).

---

## 9. Client-side security

- **Response headers** present (from §1 curl or the Network tab): `Strict-Transport-Security`, `Content-Security-Policy`, `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`, a frame-protection header (`X-Frame-Options` / CSP `frame-ancestors`), `Referrer-Policy`.
- **Cookies** (Application → Cookies): session cookies are `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, and have a sensible `SameSite`.
- **No secrets in the client:** search the JS bundle and Console for tokens, API keys, or credentials; none should be hardcoded.
- **No sensitive data in URLs** (tokens/PII shouldn't ride in query strings that land in logs/history).
- **Token storage:** confirm where the access token lives and that it's appropriate for your threat model (e.g. not a long-lived token sitting in `localStorage` if that's a concern for your team).
- **CORS** behaves — the app's own calls succeed; cross-origin calls that should be blocked are blocked.

---

## 10. Cross-browser & responsive

- Works in the browsers agents actually use (**Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge**).
- If agents use tablets/phones, verify **responsive layouts** and touch interactions.
- Reasonable behavior at different **zoom levels** and screen resolutions.

---

## 11. Performance (user-perceived)

- Initial load time is acceptable on a representative connection; run a **Lighthouse** pass for a baseline.
- **Long-session stability:** leave a device page with a live SSE stream open for a while and watch **memory** in DevTools — a steadily climbing heap suggests a leak in the stream handling.
- Large device lists render and scroll without freezing.

---

## 12. Accessibility (if in scope)

- **Keyboard navigation** reaches all interactive elements with visible focus states.
- Form fields have **labels**; images have alt text.
- **Color contrast** meets AA for text and key UI.
- Landmarks/roles present for screen-reader users.

---

## 13. Observability from the user side

- **Trigger a deliberate error** in the UI and confirm it appears in your logging/monitoring with a **correlation ID** you can trace back through the APIs.
- If a frontend error tracker (Sentry / RUM) is expected, confirm events actually arrive.

---

## Roll it up

Summarize as pass/fail with evidence, and flag any **auth/RBAC gap, control-path safety gap, or false-success behavior** prominently in the go/no-go — those are the failures that matter most on a portal that controls physical devices.
